==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Loricate
<hw>Lor"i*cate</hw> <pr>(l⟦ocr⟧r"⟦icr⟧*k⟦amac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Loricated</conjf>
<pr>(l⟦ocr⟧r"⟦icr⟧*k⟦amac⟧t`⟦ecr⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Loricating</conjf>
<pr>(l⟦ocr⟧r"⟦icr⟧*k⟦amac⟧`t⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>loricatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>loricare</ets> to clothe in mail, to
cover with plastering, fr. <ets>lorica</ets> a leather cuirass, a
plastering, fr. <ets>lorum</ets> thong.]</ety> <def>To cover with some
protecting substance, as with lute{1}, a crust, coating, or
plates.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Loricate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Loricate
<hw>Lor"i*cate</hw> <pr>(l⟦ocr⟧r"⟦icr⟧*k⟦asl⟧t)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<ety>[See <er>Loricate</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <def>Covered with a
shell or exterior made of plates somewhat like a coat of mail, as in the
armadillo.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Loricate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Loricate
<hw>Lor"i*cate</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An animal
covered with bony scales, as crocodiles among reptiles, and the
pangolins among mammals.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lorication</ent>⟦br⟧
